  <span id="freeText699650472222086771" style="display:none"><i>“But your book is wrong, Mrs. Strunk, says George, when it tells you that Jim is the substitute I found for a real son, a real kid brother, a real husband, a real wife. Jim wasn’t a substitute for anything. And there is no substitute for Jim, if you’ll forgive my saying so, anywhere.”</i><br /><br />I feel slightly conflicted because I found most of this book a struggle to get through—maybe because of the simple, colloquial writing style, or what I felt were unnecessary, distracting details. But during the last third, where the themes of love, memory, and lost time come into focus, I couldn’t help falling in love with this heartbreaking yet life-affirming meditation on loss. I’ll probably love this book even more forty years from now when I’m a (hopefully not) lonely, middle-aged gay man—especially if I’ve (hopefully not) lost someone who meant as much to me as Jim meant to George.</span>
